<font color="#FF0000">30 YEAR VISIT</font><br>
<tt>Tue May 27 20:49:07 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
It was a cloudy, overcast and humid day.  As I walked down 23rd st. from the Metro stop. I could hear the bikes on Constitution Ave. going from light to light.  As I got closer, I could see the Lincoln Memorial and I knew that I was close to my 30 year anniversary since coming home.  This weekend, actually, 5/27/67, will be 30 years.  I got to Constitution Ave. and could see the crowd of tour busses and tv vans.  It was early and I wanted to be gone before the speeches started. <br>
As I walked up on the Wall from the back, the impression is that of people disappearing into the ground. While a string of people come out.  There were patches, pins, fatigues, boonie hats and all sorts of &quot;badges&quot; identifying that &quot;I am a vet&quot;.  Today, for me, I was there not to tell all that I was a vet.  But to honor those who are not here. Those who made me the man that I am today.  After 30 years there is some closure that I want to deal with.<br>
My wife reached for my hand as we got into the line on the east side and we started the journey.  As many times that I have been to the Wall, it is always a journey.  The first time was a journey of cleansing and rebirth.  The entrance is very subtle.  The names are ankle high. As you go further into it the Wall immerses you into what it is.  A memorial of those who paid the ultimate price for freedom.  When I reached the bottom or the &quot;V&quot; I stopped for a moment.  No one pushes or shoves. It is very crowded, yet silent, respectful.  The rubbings of the names, the wreaths, the pictures lean on you until you almost can't breathe.  I feel the tears coming and my wife grips my hand harder.  She knows, she went to Vietnam too.  She felt all my pain as I started to heal, she stood by me in my craziness, and she has stood by me whenever she knows that I need her support. I look up and see the top of the Wall and then I look down and see a patch &quot;Ia Drang  '65&quot;.  Wow, I was there!  I stop the guy and welcome him home.  We talk for a few minutes and move on.  Coming out of the journey is likened by many as a rebirth.  I left a lot of s**t at the Wall.  I am moved every time that I see it.  It heals me every time that I see it.  My 30 year anniversary was a magnificent day!  It was what I needed to do and see.<br>
&quot;Lest we forget&quot; 
